<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-12-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="133" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.34537/72.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-12-04"><hi rend="italic">December 4,
                                1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1234.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt to-day of the Department’s instruction No. 411 of the 24th
                            ultimo.</p>
                        <p>I have to-day presented to the Cuban department of state a note embodying
                            the suggestions of the Secretary of the Navy. Mr. Patterson, the
                            subsecretary of state, who received me in the absence of Mr. Sanguily,
                            assured me that the matter would be given immediate attention and that
                            an answer would be given as soon as possible.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hugh S. Gibson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>